    <exercise label="chkpt-newton-geo-to-algebra">
        <title>From Tangent Line to Iteration Formula</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Match each geometric idea with the corresponding part in Newton's Method. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <feedback><p>This question reinforces how the tangent line picture becomes the iterative formula.</p></feedback>
        <cardsort>
            <match>
                <premise>Pick a point on the <m>x</m>-axis</premise>
                <response>Initial Guess: <m>x_0</m></response>
            </match>
            <match>
                <premise>Draw a tangent line at <m>(x_0,f(x_0))</m></premise>
                <response><m>y = f'(x_0)(x-x_0) + f(x_0)</m></response>
            </match>
            <match>
                <premise>Locate the point where the tangent line meets the <m>x</m>-axis, say <m>(x_1,0)</m></premise>
                <response><m>0 = f'(x_0)(x_1-x_0) + f(x_0)</m></response>
            </match>
            <match>
                <premise>Find the <m>x</m>-value of the point where the tangent hits the <m>x</m>-axis</premise>
                <response><m>x_1 = x_0 - f(x_0)/f'(x_0)</m></response>
            </match>
        </cardsort>
    </exercise>

    <p>üìçLocation: <em>After the First Figure (tangent-line visualization)</em></p>
    <exercise label="chkpt-newton-clickable-visual">
        <title>Spot the Key Step</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Click on the part of the formula for Newton's Method that represents the ‚Äúcorrection‚Äù to the current guess:
            </p>
        </statement>
        <areas>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><area correct="no"><m>x_{n+1}</m></area></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><area correct="no"><m>x_n</m></area></cell>
                    <cell><m>-</m></cell>
                    <cell><area correct="yes"><m>\dfrac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)}</m></area></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><area correct="no"><m>x_{n+1}</m></area></cell>
                    <cell><m>=</m></cell>
                    <cell><area correct="no"><m>x_n</m></area></cell>
                    <cell><m>-</m></cell>
                    <cell><area correct="yes"><m>\dfrac{f(x_n)}{f'(x_n)}</m></area></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </areas>
        <feedback>
            <p>
            The fraction <m>f(x_n)/f'(x_n)</m> is the adjustment step ‚Äî it represents how far along the tangent line we move from <m>x_n</m> to find <m>x_{n+1}</m>.
            </p>
        </feedback>
    </exercise>

    <p>üìçLocation: <em>After the Worked Example (cube root polynomial)</em></p>
    <exercise label="chkpt-newton-initial-guess">
    <title>The Role of the Initial Guess</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
        Which of the following is the best reason why Newton's Method succeeded even with the initial guess <m>x_0=1</m> not being very close to the root of <m>x^3-x^2-1=0</m>?
        </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
        <statement><p>Because Newton's Method always works no matter where you start.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Not true‚Äîsometimes it diverges. The success here was not guaranteed.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>Because the tangent lines in this case still led toward the root despite a rough initial guess.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct‚ÄîNewton's Method is often robust to imperfect starting points.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>Because the derivative was zero at <m>x=1</m>.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Incorrect‚Äîthe derivative was not zero; a zero derivative would actually make Newton's Method fail.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
    </choices>
    </exercise>

    <p>üìçLocation: <em>After the Calculator/ANS Key Discussion</em></p>
    <exercise label="chkpt-newton-stopping">
    <title>Stopping Rule</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
        Which stopping condition is typically used in Newton's Method when using technology?
        </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>When successive approximations agree to the desired number of decimal places.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct‚Äîdecimal agreement ensures accuracy to that many places.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>When the derivative <m>f'(x)</m> becomes zero.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Not correct‚Äîa zero derivative may cause failure, not a stopping point.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>After exactly 10 iterations, regardless of accuracy.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Iteration count alone does not guarantee accuracy.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
    </choices>
    </exercise>

    <p>üìçLocation: <em>In the Convergence/Fails Section (cube root example)</em></p>
    <exercise label="chkpt-newton-failure">
    <title>When Newton's Method Fails</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
        Select all situations where Newton's Method may fail to converge.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>When <m>f'(x_n)=0</m> for some approximation.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct‚Äîdivision by zero breaks the formula.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>When the initial guess is always greater than the true root.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Not necessarily‚Äîbeing greater or less isn't the key issue, the behavior of the tangent lines is.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>When tangent lines push approximations farther away from the root (as in <m>f(x)=x^{1/3}</m>).</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct‚Äîhere each step doubled the distance from the root.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>When the function is continuous and differentiable everywhere.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>No‚Äîcontinuity and differentiability are necessary, not failure conditions.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
    </choices>
    </exercise>

    <p>üìçLocation: <em>?</em></p>
    <exercise label="chkpt-newton-applications">
    <title>Where Newton's Method Fits</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
        Select all situations where Newton's Method would be a reasonable tool.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>Approximating the solution to <m>\cos(x)=x</m>.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct‚Äîthis equation cannot be solved algebraically but Newton's Method can approximate the solution.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>Finding the exact solution to <m>x^2=9</m>.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Not needed‚Äîthis equation has an exact solution, so Newton's Method is unnecessary.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>Programming a calculator or computer to approximate roots efficiently.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct‚ÄîNewton's Method is fast and widely used in computational root finding.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
        <statement><p>Estimating the slope of a tangent line at a point.</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>No‚ÄîNewton's Method uses tangent slopes, but its goal is to find roots, not slopes.</p></feedback>
        </choice>
    </choices>
    </exercise>

